title: #pov : Parents millionnaires → pas possible d'acheter quoi que ce soit... 🤑❌
description:
Chloé is fifteen years old, lives in a luxurious villa in Cannes, with an infinity pool, a garden full of exotic flowers, and parents who own a chain of hotels around the world. Everyone at school thinks she has a dream life: millionaire parents 🤑, luxury cars, vacations in the most expensive destinations. But no one knows her secret: despite her family’s wealth, her parents never buy her anything she wants. No new phone, no designer clothes, no jewelry, not even a small coffee with her friends after school. #pov : Millionaire parents → can’t buy anything... 🤑❌ – that’s Chloé’s reality, a reality that has made her bitter and confused for years.
It started when she was seven. For her birthday, she had asked for a luxury doll, the same one her friend Léa had. Her parents, Sophie and Marc, had smiled and said: “Chloé, we can’t buy that for you. You’ll have to get it yourself, if you really want it.” Chloé had cried for hours, not understanding: how could parents who had millions of dollars not buy a simple doll? Since that day, it was the same: every request was refused, with the same explanation: “Happiness can’t be bought, and the value of something is measured by the effort you put into it.”

At fifteen, Chloé had become a shy and somewhat isolated teenager. Her friends talked about their new fashion outfits, their vacations in Saint-Tropez, their latest phones, while she wore simple clothes bought in ordinary stores, used a second-hand phone, and spent her weekends at home, helping the maid garden or reading in the villa’s library. One day, after school, her friends invited her to go to the mall to buy new makeup. “I can’t,” Chloé said, hanging her head. “My parents don’t give me money, and they don’t buy me anything.” Her friends laughed: “Are you kidding? Your parents are millionaires! You’re pretending to be poor for attention?” Chloé was embarrassed and ran away, tears in her eyes.

Back home, she ran to her room, closed the door and cried. Her parents heard her sobs and came to see her. “Chloé, what’s wrong?” her mother asked, sitting next to her. “Why do you never give me anything?” Chloé shouted, wiping her tears. “Everyone thinks I have a perfect life, but I’m the only one who has nothing! You’re millionaires, but you treat me like a poor person! Why?”

Marc, her father, took her hand and said calmly: “Chloé, we know this is hard for you. But we’re not doing this to punish you; we’re doing this to protect you. When I was young, my parents were very poor. I had to work hard from the age of twelve: delivering newspapers in the morning, helping in a restaurant in the evening, to pay for my studies. It was thanks to that effort that I succeeded, that I built my hotels, that we have this life today. We’re afraid that if we buy you everything you want, you’ll never understand the value of work, you won’t know how to appreciate things, and you’ll become dependent on money.”

Her mother added: “We’ve seen many young people who had everything in life, thanks to their rich parents. But most of them became lazy, superficial, unable to face difficulties. They think money can solve everything, but that’s not true. We want you to become a strong, independent woman, who knows how to manage her own affairs, who appreciates every thing she gets, because she worked hard for it.”

Chloé didn’t understand everything right away, but she stopped crying. Her father continued: “If you want a new phone, if you want to go to the mall with your friends, you can. But you’ll have to work to earn money. We’ll give you a small job in our office: answering emails, organizing documents, helping the employees. Every hour of work, you’ll earn money, and you can buy what you want with that money. Does that sound good?”

Chloé nodded, a little hesitant. The next day, she started her job in her parents’ office. At first, it was hard: she had to get up early, work for two hours after school, learn to use the software, answer calls. But over the weeks, she started to like it: she felt useful, she was earning her money with her own effort. After a month, she had earned enough money to buy a new phone and some makeup. She went to the mall with her friends and bought what she wanted. But this time, it was different: she knew how many hours she had worked to earn that money, and she appreciated every thing more than ever.

La mythique recette de crêpes « parfumées » de Raymond Oliver 🥞

… diffusée dans l’émission « Art et Magie de la cuisine » en 1957, il y a presque 70 ans ! Il est accompagné des commentaires hilarants de Catherine Langeais 🤌

Un classique absolu des « recettes vintage » de @l’INA, à retrouver sur leur site web bien sûr ❤️

INGRÉDIENTS :(Pour 4 personnes, à condition d’en manger 24 ou 30 chacune… !)400 g de farine8 œufs250 ml de lait entier100 g de beurre5 cuillères à soupe de sucre2 grosses pincées de sel2 cuillères à soupe d’huile neutre
Puis pour le « parfum » :250 ml de rhum ambré50 ml de pastis75 cl de bière blonde1 gousse de vanille

Je peux confirmer qu’on sent bien les effets de l’alcool même après la cuisson, donc pour un goûter en famille ce ne sera peut-être pas la meilleure option. (Pour une fringale en after, pourquoi pas… !) La pâte est suffisamment grasse, donc pas besoin de beurrer la poêle (par contre, vous, vous allez l’être)… 🤣

Vous pouvez regarder la chaîne de Tom Cooks, qui a fait une belle vidéo en format long sur cette recette de crêpes.

Bon appétit !

title: Dimanche matin (1961) de John Falter #art #histoiredelart #peinture
description:
Le tableau de John Falter, « Dimanche matin » (1961), est une opposition brillante entre deux philosophies de vie. Sur la gauche, nous voyons M. Jones, l'incarnation de la discipline et du travail acharné. Sa maison est dans un état impeccable, sa pelouse est tondue avec une précision mathématique, et lui-même est déjà à l'œuvre. Sa vie est une quête permanente de perfection.

Le côté droit du tableau présente l'exact opposé. Le voisin de M. Jones a choisi le repos total. Sa maison est délabrée, sa cour envahie de mauvaises herbes, et lui-même dort paisiblement sur le porche, couvert d'un journal. Falter souligne l'ironie : tandis qu'un voisin taille ses buissons, l'autre laisse un pic-vert s'attaquer à sa maison.

Cette œuvre pose une question universelle : qu'est-ce qui est le plus important, une apparence irréprochable ou la tranquillité d'esprit ? D'un côté, l'ordre admirable de Jones, de l'autre, la liberté nonchalante de son voisin. Et vous, de quel côté penchez-vous ce dimanche ? Préférez-vous tailler vos haies ou savourer une sieste bien méritée ?

title: Voici l'iPhone Fold qui remplace l'iPhone 18 en 2026 !
description:
Apple préparerait enfin son premier iPhone pliable : l’iPhone Fold.
Un produit attendu depuis des années, entouré de rumeurs, de brevets et de fuites… et qui pourrait bien arriver en 2026.

Collaboration commerciale avec Ubigi.
10% de réduction sur le forfait ici : https://go.ubigi.com/VxxJ26 
---------------------------------------------------
Dans cette vidéo, je récapitule toutes les informations crédibles connues à ce jour sur l’iPhone Fold :
le format inédit choisi par Apple, les raisons pour lesquelles la marque a attendu aussi longtemps avant de se lancer, les choix techniques autour de l’écran pliable, de la pliure, du verre, de la charnière, mais aussi l’impact que tout ça pourrait avoir sur le logiciel et l’expérience utilisateur.
On parle notamment :
– du format large, pensé pour être agréable même lorsque le téléphone est fermé
– d’un écran interne proche d’un iPad mini pliable
– des rumeurs autour d’un écran quasi sans pli visible
– des technologies évoquées pour gérer la pliure (structure interne, traitement du verre, matériaux avancés)
– d’un possible écran à auto-réparation (oui, vraiment)
– de l’évolution d’iOS vers une expérience plus hybride entre iPhone et iPad
– des questions autour de Face ID, Touch ID, de l’épaisseur et du design
– des performances, de la batterie, du prix et de la date de sortie

⚠️ Important :
Cette vidéo est basée sur des rumeurs, fuites et analyses, et non sur un produit final. Je n’ai évidemment jamais pris l’iPhone Fold en main : certaines parties relèvent donc de suppositions logiques, toujours clairement assumées.
L’objectif ici n’est pas de faire du sensationnel, mais de comprendre la vision d’Apple, les enjeux techniques, et pourquoi l’iPhone Fold pourrait être très différent des pliables actuels.

Circuit Breaker Finder ⚡️
description:
A circuit breaker finder works like a high-tech game of Marco Polo played through your home’s hidden wires. When you plug the transmitter into an outlet, it injects a unique digital "shout" into the copper wiring that travels all the way back to the breaker panel. This signal is a specific frequency that hitches a ride on the electrical current, acting like a secret code moving through a crowded pipe.

To find the match, you move the handheld receiver over the rows of switches. This device uses a sensor to detect the invisible electromagnetic field created by that specific signal. It is programmed to ignore the standard hum of electricity and only listen for its partner's voice. When the receiver passes over the correct breaker, the magnetic field is strongest, triggering a beep and a light. This allows you to pinpoint exactly which switch controls which room without any tedious trial and error.

How This Cheap PS5 Controller Has Features Like THIS?! #playstation5 #gaming
description:
In this video, I'm comparing two incredible gaming controllers in The Last of Us Part 2: the standard PlayStation 5 controller and Razer's latest pro controller built for hardcore gamers. The standard PS5 DualSense has all the next-gen features, even in a game like TLOU 2 that was made for PS4 six years ago and remastered for PS5, including adaptive triggers, haptic feedback, and those new vibrations. On the other hand, the Razer controller could've done better since it's missing those features, but it makes up for it with extra buttons by R1 and R2 and on the back. Also, the Razer controller lets you make R2 feel like a mouse click, which is amazing and lets you shoot way faster in Last of Us 2, something the PS5 controller can't do, and even the DualSense Edge isn't quite this good. In this video, I wanted to compare how the controllers feel and show how much of a deep, unique vibe the standard PS5 DualSense gives gamers with different weapons at a much lower price.
